I don't think he was -- I don't
think he really had much popular

00:54:32.670 --> 00:54:36.300
appeal, but what about if
there hadn't been some guy

00:54:36.300 --> 00:54:38.610
like Luther, as forceful,
as charismatic,

00:54:38.610 --> 00:54:43.260
as belligerent in
his viewpoints?

00:54:43.260 --> 00:54:46.180
Would the Reformation
have occurred?

00:54:46.180 --> 00:54:47.480
&gt;&gt; Brad Gregory:
Yeah, so this is one

00:54:47.480 --> 00:54:50.720
of those giant what historians
call counterfactual questions.

00:54:50.720 --> 00:54:52.210
If it hadn't been
for Luther, right,

00:54:52.210 --> 00:54:54.110
then what would have happened?

00:54:54.110 --> 00:54:56.550
One of the difficulties of
trying to answer a question

00:54:56.550 --> 00:55:00.460
like this about a
phenomenon that, if even half

00:55:00.460 --> 00:55:03.030
of what I've argued tonight
is right, the Reformation was

00:55:03.030 --> 00:55:07.300
so dramatically transformative,
it's hard to imagine

00:55:07.300 --> 00:55:08.600
if it hadn't happened, well,

00:55:08.600 --> 00:55:09.900
how might things have
transpired differently.

00:55:09.900 --> 00:55:15.890
So that's the dodge aspect of
my answer to your question.

00:55:15.890 --> 00:55:18.580
I think -- well,
there's certainly --

00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:21.200
there are all kinds
of reform initiatives

00:55:21.200 --> 00:55:23.920
and so forth underway
prior to Martin Luther.

00:55:23.920 --> 00:55:27.280
This has been one of the really
important, I think, developments

00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:28.920
in scholarship on
the late Middle Ages

00:55:28.920 --> 00:55:32.100
and the early 16th
century in recent decades.

00:55:32.100 --> 00:55:34.810
You mention Erasmus, and I mean
I think it's very interesting,

00:55:34.810 --> 00:55:38.650
because Erasmian humanism
and Erasmus' vision

00:55:38.650 --> 00:55:40.400
for the gradual reform

00:55:40.400 --> 00:55:42.800
of Christendom is very
different from Luther's.

00:55:42.800 --> 00:55:46.800
It's based primarily
on patient education.

00:55:46.800 --> 00:55:50.040
Humanist scholars, no
surprise, are the heroes.

00:55:50.040 --> 00:55:52.070
They're the ones who
have the languages

00:55:52.070 --> 00:55:53.600
and are doing the philological

00:55:53.600 --> 00:55:56.250
and the scholarly research
that's going to go back

00:55:56.250 --> 00:55:58.820
to the sources, as
they say, ad fontes,

00:55:58.820 --> 00:56:02.930
and by producing reliable
editions of the scriptures,

00:56:02.930 --> 00:56:05.290
as Erasmus himself
did -- well, reliable.

00:56:05.290 --> 00:56:10.610
Not by the criteria of
contemporary biblical scholars,

00:56:10.610 --> 00:56:12.620
but very much so at the time.

00:56:12.620 --> 00:56:17.330
His edition of the 1516 New
Testament with facing text,

00:56:17.330 --> 00:56:21.810
Latin and Greek is incredibly
important, but the question is:

00:56:21.810 --> 00:56:26.450
You know, what might Erasmian
humanism have achieved had,

00:56:26.450 --> 00:56:28.150
you know, there not
been someone, again,

00:56:28.150 --> 00:56:30.870
as sort of insistent
and, as you said,

00:56:30.870 --> 00:56:33.060
belligerent as Martin Luther?

00:56:33.060 --> 00:56:36.140
There certainly are other
reformers who reject Rome

00:56:36.140 --> 00:56:38.130
in the course of the 1520s

00:56:38.130 --> 00:56:40.590
who have personalities very
different from Martin Luther.

00:56:40.590 --> 00:56:44.800
Huldrych Zwingli can be nasty,
but nothing like Luther.

00:56:44.800 --> 00:56:47.940
And so I think, you know, in
the end, we're left with sort

00:56:47.940 --> 00:56:51.190
of speculative, interesting
discussion, fun discussion

00:56:51.190 --> 00:56:53.910
to talk about over a beer, but
I think it's really impossible

00:56:53.910 --> 00:56:59.080
to resolve in any kind of
compelling or kind of, you know,

00:56:59.080 --> 00:57:03.160
universally persuasive way what
might have transpired instead

00:57:03.160 --> 00:57:05.880
without -- major historical
counterfactuals, I think,

00:57:05.880 --> 00:57:07.690
simply have that character.

00:57:07.690 --> 00:57:10.710
Thanks. Yes, sir?

00:57:10.710 --> 00:57:14.260
&gt;&gt; I'm just curious.

00:57:14.260 --> 00:57:17.520
I would like to hear
your thoughts

00:57:17.520 --> 00:57:25.670
about the second large religion,
Islam, which has had this schism

00:57:25.670 --> 00:57:28.900
between the Sunni and the
Shiite for centuries, for much,

00:57:28.900 --> 00:57:33.730
much longer than the
Catholicism and Martin Luther,

00:57:33.730 --> 00:57:38.080
which after a couple of
hundreds years of vicious wars,

00:57:38.080 --> 00:57:42.140
Thirty Years' War, other wars,
came to an understanding and led

00:57:42.140 --> 00:57:47.250
to the religious freedom
which you espoused here.

00:57:47.250 --> 00:57:52.940
What do you foresee, if
anything, in speculations?

00:57:52.940 --> 00:57:57.780
Is there a possibility between
the Sunni and the Shiite,

00:57:57.780 --> 00:58:01.500
which have been fighting each
other for over a thousand years,

00:58:01.500 --> 00:58:03.740
well over a thousand
years, that they would come

00:58:03.740 --> 00:58:08.190
to an accommodation at
any time in the future

00:58:08.190 --> 00:58:12.590
like there has been development
in the Christian world?

00:58:12.590 --> 00:58:15.970
&gt;&gt; Brad Gregory: Well, I have
a dodge on this question, too.

00:58:15.970 --> 00:58:19.830
The question is prospects for
the relationship between Sunni

00:58:19.830 --> 00:58:22.490
and Shia Muslims in
terms of reconciliation

00:58:22.490 --> 00:58:26.650
in the future analogous
to that, the kind of ways

00:58:26.650 --> 00:58:28.770
of accommodating
coexistence that Protestants

00:58:28.770 --> 00:58:31.170
and Catholics have to
large extent achieved

00:58:31.170 --> 00:58:33.360
in the modern world in the west.

00:58:33.360 --> 00:58:36.470
My dodge on this is I'm
not a scholar of Islam.

00:58:36.470 --> 00:58:38.820
I really am not, so
I'm not -- the other --

00:58:38.820 --> 00:58:40.940
it's fascinating to me.

00:58:40.940 --> 00:58:43.040
One, I get a counterfactual
question

00:58:43.040 --> 00:58:44.810
about if Luther hadn't
come along,

00:58:44.810 --> 00:58:46.730
how might everything have
been different in the past,

00:58:46.730 --> 00:58:49.330
and now I get a question about,
you know, what do you foresee

00:58:49.330 --> 00:58:51.270
in the future about the
relationship between --

00:58:51.270 --> 00:58:53.370
you know, I'm just
a humble historian.

00:58:53.370 --> 00:58:58.650
I try to study what actually
happened and how it played out.

00:58:58.650 --> 00:59:06.300
That said, I mean, well, the
relationship of different groups

00:59:06.300 --> 00:59:10.060
within Islam, including, most
importantly, Sunni and Shia,

00:59:10.060 --> 00:59:12.630
but they're not the only
ones, is, of course,

00:59:12.630 --> 00:59:16.420
one important dimension of the
kinds of conflicts and unrest

00:59:16.420 --> 00:59:18.590
that we see in not
only the Middle East,

00:59:18.590 --> 00:59:20.420
other parts of the
world, and so forth.

00:59:20.420 --> 00:59:23.830
Another critically
important part is the ways

00:59:23.830 --> 00:59:27.100
in which western powers
intervened in the Middle East

00:59:27.100 --> 00:59:29.090
in the late 19th and
early 20th centuries

00:59:29.090 --> 00:59:30.830
and arbitrarily divided up,

00:59:30.830 --> 00:59:33.000
sliced and diced different
countries, and so forth,

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:36.500
and created problems because
of the borders that they drew

00:59:36.500 --> 00:59:38.800
in ways that were
not there before.

00:59:38.800 --> 00:59:41.970
So many of the problems
that we see

00:59:41.970 --> 00:59:46.590
in the Islamic world today are
at least difficult to extricate

00:59:46.590 --> 00:59:49.440
from the western
interventions of the last,

00:59:49.440 --> 00:59:51.960
say, century and a half.

00:59:51.960 --> 00:59:54.580
Another crucially important
question, and one I think

00:59:54.580 --> 00:59:57.110
that many westerners
are at least

00:59:57.110 --> 01:00:00.410
as concerned with, is about --

01:00:00.410 --> 01:00:03.640
-- the ways in which Muslims,
whether Sunni, or Shia,

01:00:03.640 --> 01:00:07.690
or from some other group,
are likely to, able to,

01:00:07.690 --> 01:00:11.570
or willing to make the
sort of accommodation

01:00:11.570 --> 01:00:15.350
that most liberal westerners
hope that they will make,

01:00:15.350 --> 01:00:17.310
and that, it seems to me,

01:00:17.310 --> 01:00:19.950
is maybe even a more
pressing question than the one

01:00:19.950 --> 01:00:22.930
about the relationship
between Sunni and Shia.

01:00:22.930 --> 01:00:27.920
I'll make just one sort
of side comment on that.

01:00:27.920 --> 01:00:31.200
It seems to me, and I say
this partly from my reading

01:00:31.200 --> 01:00:35.420
and also partly from talking
to some Muslim friends,

01:00:35.420 --> 01:00:40.710
they look at certain aspects
of western society and see it

01:00:40.710 --> 01:00:43.680
as a negative lesson in what
they don't want to happen

01:00:43.680 --> 01:00:46.520
to their own societies
and the ways in which --

01:00:46.520 --> 01:00:48.830
when I talk about religion
as more than religion here

01:00:48.830 --> 01:00:51.610
in the early 16th century,
religion is more than religion

01:00:51.610 --> 01:00:54.060
in Muslim societies today, too,

01:00:54.060 --> 01:00:57.240
even ones that are relatively
liberal, to say nothing

01:00:57.240 --> 01:01:01.470
of the ones that have the kind
of tightest interwoven aspect

01:01:01.470 --> 01:01:04.620
of Islam with all dimensions
of life, and when they look

01:01:04.620 --> 01:01:08.080
at the west, for example,
and they say, "Yeah,

01:01:08.080 --> 01:01:10.390
you say it's awful what
we do to our women,

01:01:10.390 --> 01:01:14.710
but look at the widespread
pornography on every available,

01:01:14.710 --> 01:01:18.650
right, downloadable laptop
everywhere in the western world.

01:01:18.650 --> 01:01:20.450
Which one of those
is worse, you know?"

01:01:20.450 --> 01:01:22.240
I've had Muslim friends
say things like that to me.

01:01:22.240 --> 01:01:26.480
So the only point being I don't
think it's a simple problem,

01:01:26.480 --> 01:01:31.530
and I don't think that all
the aces are held by the west.

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:35.510
Yes, in the back.

01:01:36.590 --> 01:01:41.510
&gt;&gt; If religion and Christianity
-- before the Reformation,

01:01:41.510 --> 01:01:47.840
I would say that it
held us together.

01:01:47.840 --> 01:01:51.470
It was like a skeleton
or a basis

01:01:51.470 --> 01:01:56.170
on which people were informed as
to how to behave, how to live,

01:01:56.170 --> 01:01:59.480
how to do business,
interact with each other,

01:01:59.480 --> 01:02:02.720
not just what to believe, right.

01:02:02.720 --> 01:02:04.180
&gt;&gt; Brad Gregory: Yeah,
about practice as much --

01:02:04.180 --> 01:02:06.710
in fact, practice even
more, in some ways,

01:02:06.710 --> 01:02:08.010
than explicit beliefs.

01:02:08.010 --> 01:02:11.180
&gt;&gt; Well, now, recently, I
spent 11 years living in India

01:02:11.180 --> 01:02:15.080
with Tibetan refugees,
and they, too, live --

01:02:15.080 --> 01:02:18.730
they live their religion.

01:02:18.730 --> 01:02:20.820
It informs everything --

01:02:20.820 --> 01:02:22.120
&gt;&gt; Brad Gregory: Right.

01:02:22.120 --> 01:02:25.610
&gt;&gt; -- they do, and I
see when they leave,

01:02:28.430 --> 01:02:29.590
because many are trying
to leave, when they come

01:02:29.590 --> 01:02:36.220
to the west and they no longer
live in that society, they, too,

01:02:36.220 --> 01:02:41.740
like us -- I mean it was the
glue that held them together

01:02:41.740 --> 01:02:44.420
and held their culture together.

01:02:44.420 --> 01:02:48.900
Well, what you have just
described is we are all

01:02:48.900 --> 01:02:50.430
drifting apart.

01:02:50.430 --> 01:02:54.360
We're drifting further and
further away from anything

01:02:54.360 --> 01:03:00.210
that we can all recognize
and value,

01:03:00.210 --> 01:03:02.120
and if that is the case --

01:03:02.120 --> 01:03:06.400
and I have another example
as a retired schoolteacher.

01:03:06.400 --> 01:03:08.880
I see that in our schools.

01:03:08.880 --> 01:03:14.440
Our schools no longer teach
the basic, classical education.

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:21.230
They just don't, and so
now, I was just talking

01:03:21.230 --> 01:03:26.570
to an intern today, and he
said, "Nowadays in school,

01:03:26.570 --> 01:03:32.250
kids just focus on what
kind of job they want.

01:03:32.250 --> 01:03:37.230
That's what they're focused on."

01:03:37.230 --> 01:03:39.360
So let's say somebody wants

01:03:39.360 --> 01:03:45.110
to be a mathematician,
so they study math.

01:03:45.110 --> 01:03:52.240
They don't know anything else,
so who do they relate to?

01:03:52.240 --> 01:03:56.340
Who can they relate to?

01:03:56.340 --> 01:03:57.640
&gt;&gt; Brad Gregory: Yeah.

01:03:57.640 --> 01:03:59.470
&gt;&gt; Another mathematician,
you know, but not the rest

01:03:59.470 --> 01:04:03.180
of the world, so
even our own society,

01:04:03.180 --> 01:04:07.340
as you're suggesting,
is drifting apart.

01:04:07.340 --> 01:04:09.970
There's nothing to hold
us together anymore,

01:04:09.970 --> 01:04:13.390
and if there is, please
tell us what it is.

01:04:13.390 --> 01:04:14.690
&gt;&gt; Brad Gregory: Hey, you
know, you're preaching

01:04:14.690 --> 01:04:16.140
to the choir on that one.

01:04:16.140 --> 01:04:19.100
I mean that's very close to
my analysis of the situation

01:04:19.100 --> 01:04:20.400
in which we find ourselves.

01:04:20.400 --> 01:04:21.730
I published a book
several years ago --

01:04:21.730 --> 01:04:24.600
Nicholas mentioned it
in his introduction --

01:04:24.600 --> 01:04:28.760
called The Unintended
Reformation,

01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:32.080
in which I said some things
about the kind of divisiveness

01:04:32.080 --> 01:04:37.480
and the dividedness of
particularly Americans,

01:04:37.480 --> 01:04:41.670
but we can see it also
in different guises

01:04:41.670 --> 01:04:44.210
in western European
countries as well.

01:04:44.210 --> 01:04:51.040
That was published in 2012, and
it was really interesting to me.

01:04:51.040 --> 01:04:54.790
During the course of the
election, before November

01:04:54.790 --> 01:04:58.610
of 2016, I got a number
of emails from readers

01:04:58.610 --> 01:05:05.670
of that book saying, "So I mean
it's scary how spot-on you were,

01:05:05.670 --> 01:05:12.640
you know, about this," because
there was an important debate

01:05:12.640 --> 01:05:18.460
among observers and
analysts in the United States

01:05:18.460 --> 01:05:21.290
in recent years about, you know,

01:05:21.290 --> 01:05:25.870
"Is there really culture
wars in the United States?

01:05:25.870 --> 01:05:28.410
Oh, it's just some
small, vocal minorities.

01:05:28.410 --> 01:05:33.480
Really, most Americans agree and
can get along with one another,"

01:05:33.480 --> 01:05:38.080
and I think -- I mean now, we'd
be hard pressed to find anybody,

01:05:38.080 --> 01:05:40.190
I think, who would
defend the view

01:05:40.190 --> 01:05:45.420
that it's not really
deeply divided.

01:05:45.420 --> 01:05:47.700
The question then, of
course, is, you know,

01:05:47.700 --> 01:05:49.540
really, where do we turn?

01:05:49.540 --> 01:05:53.040
What are the, you know, possible
alternatives for something

01:05:53.040 --> 01:05:55.350
that could, you know, function?

01:05:55.350 --> 01:05:57.860
What's deeply troubling
to me and many others --

01:05:57.860 --> 01:06:00.350
again, I'm not saying
anything that probably all

01:06:00.350 --> 01:06:02.040
of you haven't heard ad nauseam

01:06:02.040 --> 01:06:03.560
in the last year in
terms of analysis.

01:06:03.560 --> 01:06:06.450
What's particularly disturbing
is what I would call a crisis

01:06:06.450 --> 01:06:08.180
of shared epistemology.

01:06:08.180 --> 01:06:11.520
By that I mean we don't even
agree on what the sources

01:06:11.520 --> 01:06:14.350
of our information
are to be able

01:06:14.350 --> 01:06:17.160
to have a shared discussion,
so the determination

01:06:17.160 --> 01:06:24.610
of what is the case, the facts,
are, well, you know, "No,

01:06:24.610 --> 01:06:29.400
I'll get mine from Breitbart.

01:06:29.400 --> 01:06:32.620
You get yours from MSNBC."

01:06:32.620 --> 01:06:36.390
You know, it's impossible
to have a shared discussion

01:06:36.390 --> 01:06:39.910
if you don't agree substantially
on what the [inaudible] are.

01:06:39.910 --> 01:06:44.000
I don't have an answer to that.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:46.290
Again, this is amazing.

01:06:46.290 --> 01:06:50.090
It's like how would
you speculate

01:06:50.090 --> 01:06:55.740
that the past would have
been utterly different

01:06:55.740 --> 01:06:58.790
without Luther, what do
you think's going to happen

01:06:58.790 --> 01:07:05.000
to Muslims in the future,
and please give us the answer

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:07.840
to our incredibly
divided problems.

01:07:07.840 --> 01:07:09.140
No problem.

01:07:09.140 --> 01:07:12.730
That's what historians
are trained to do.

01:07:12.730 --> 01:07:16.530
So anyway, maybe we have
time for one more question.

01:07:16.530 --> 01:07:17.830
Yeah, sir, in the back?

01:07:17.830 --> 01:07:20.340
&gt;&gt; It may be a question,
may be more of a comment.

01:07:20.340 --> 01:07:23.780
You talked about basically how
after the Thirty Years' War,

01:07:23.780 --> 01:07:27.970
things started to -- the
church basically went

01:07:27.970 --> 01:07:29.530
to a very scholastic place,

01:07:29.530 --> 01:07:32.450
but I think there was
still a cultural divide

01:07:32.450 --> 01:07:35.630
between the intellectual,
philosophical part of the church

01:07:35.630 --> 01:07:41.890
and the pietistic movement in
Europe that eventually came here

01:07:41.890 --> 01:07:47.480
in this country that brought us
the two Great Awakenings a very

01:07:47.480 --> 01:07:50.390
conservative religious
movement that continues,

01:07:50.390 --> 01:07:53.660
possibly through the Charismatic
movement, to this day,

01:07:53.660 --> 01:07:58.990
where the church itself has
divided again, in a certain way.

01:07:58.990 --> 01:08:00.790
Could you comment about that?

01:08:00.790 --> 01:08:03.150
&gt;&gt; Brad Gregory: Well, I mean
there really never is a point

01:08:03.150 --> 01:08:05.870
from even the early
decades of the Reformation

01:08:05.870 --> 01:08:08.620
in the 16th century
when Protestantism seen

01:08:08.620 --> 01:08:10.910
as a whole doesn't
encompass an enormous variety

01:08:10.910 --> 01:08:12.700
of different movements,
churches, organizations,

01:08:12.700 --> 01:08:16.160
and so forth, so yes, of
course, I mean in terms

01:08:16.160 --> 01:08:19.820
of whether we're talking about
an anglophone context and, say,

01:08:19.820 --> 01:08:23.930
talking about Methodism and
John Wesley in the 18th century

01:08:23.930 --> 01:08:29.720
as a kind of intra-Anglican
pietistic movement, say,

01:08:29.720 --> 01:08:31.170
that's parallel to what's going

01:08:31.170 --> 01:08:34.770
on in German-speaking
territories with respect

01:08:34.770 --> 01:08:40.150
to Lutheranism, because pietism,
the usual meaning of pietism

01:08:40.150 --> 01:08:43.120
that starts in the
early 17th century,

01:08:43.120 --> 01:08:45.090
with people like
Arndt and others.

01:08:45.090 --> 01:08:47.330
Those are absolutely part of,

01:08:47.330 --> 01:08:50.570
would fit into what I was
talking when I'm talking

01:08:50.570 --> 01:08:52.430
about the constructive
aspects, right,

01:08:52.430 --> 01:08:55.230
of the religious traditions that
come out of the Reformation era,

01:08:55.230 --> 01:08:59.630
not only the various Protestant
traditions, but also Catholicism

01:08:59.630 --> 01:09:01.450
that will develop and continue
to the present day as well.

01:09:01.450 --> 01:09:05.530
So yes, that is absolutely
part of the story.

01:09:05.530 --> 01:09:07.330
It fits into the picture
that I've described here,

01:09:07.330 --> 01:09:10.880
because once we get
into the modern world,

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:12.410
you can be a pietist,
you can be a Unitarian,

01:09:12.410 --> 01:09:13.710
you can be a Quaker,
you can be a Catholic,

01:09:13.710 --> 01:09:15.010
you can be a Charismatic,

01:09:15.010 --> 01:09:16.310
you can be whatever you
want to be, you know.

01:09:16.310 --> 01:09:17.610
The point is you can be
whatever you want to.

01:09:17.610 --> 01:09:18.910
Religious freedom is politically
protected, but you know,

01:09:18.910 --> 01:09:20.210
we're not going to share any
of that, right, in common.

01:09:20.210 --> 01:09:21.510
It's not going to be proscribed.

01:09:21.510 --> 01:09:22.810
You can believe whatever
you want

01:09:22.810 --> 01:09:24.110
so long as you obey the laws.

01:09:24.110 --> 01:09:25.410
That's the basic way in which
the problem of Christianity

01:09:25.410 --> 01:09:26.710
from the Reformation era
is attempted to be solved.

01:09:26.710 --> 01:09:28.010
For most of US history,
for a long time,

01:09:28.010 --> 01:09:29.310
certainly when Tocqueville
visits in the early 1830s,

01:09:29.310 --> 01:09:30.610
he looks, and he
sees, "Incredible.

01:09:30.610 --> 01:09:31.910
Look at this.

01:09:31.910 --> 01:09:33.210
All these different
Protestant groups.

01:09:33.210 --> 01:09:34.510
Even got a smattering of
Catholics and so forth,

01:09:34.510 --> 01:09:35.810
even a handful of Jews, right."

01:09:35.810 --> 01:09:37.110
He says, "All the
Christian groups, right,

01:09:37.110 --> 01:09:38.410
they all worship God
in different ways,

01:09:38.410 --> 01:09:39.710
yet they all share
the same morality.

01:09:39.710 --> 01:09:41.010
They all share a sense of
duty, and of public mindedness,

01:09:41.010 --> 01:09:42.310
and what it is that
people owe to one another."

01:09:42.310 --> 01:09:43.610
That's what's gone.

01:09:43.610 --> 01:09:44.910
That's what dissipated, and I
think in ways that are parallel

01:09:44.910 --> 01:09:46.210
to the decline of the so-called
mainstream Protestant churches

01:09:46.210 --> 01:09:47.510
in the United States, because
they were the cultural backbone

01:09:47.510 --> 01:09:48.810
of that phenomenon.

01:09:48.810 --> 01:09:50.110
So that's a situation
in which it seems

01:09:50.110 --> 01:09:51.410
to me we find ourselves,
but absolutely,

01:09:51.410 --> 01:09:52.710
those Protestant traditions
that you're talking about,

01:09:52.710 --> 01:09:54.010
that originated in Europe,
came across the Atlantic,

01:09:54.010 --> 01:09:55.310
have definitely had an influence
here, as have the others.

